'''''Quest for the Rings''''' is a [[board game]]/[[video game]] hybrid for the [[Magnavox Odyssey²]]. It is the first game in the Odyssey² "Master Strategy Series",<ref name=kunkel82nov>{{cite journal |last1= Kunkel |first1= Bill |author-link1= Bill Kunkel (gaming)|last2= Katz |first2= Arnie |author-link2= Arnie Katz|date= November 1982 |title= Video's Guide to Electronic Games |journal= [[Video (magazine)|Video]]|publisher= Reese Communications|volume= 6|issue= 8|pages= 47–56, 108|issn= 0147-8907}}</ref>{{rp|53}} and contemporary reviews described it as innovative.

==Gameplay==
The game supports one to three players.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kunkel |first1=Bill |last2=Katz |first2=Arnie |title=THE VIDEOGAMES: HOW THEY RATE (Published 1981) |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1981/11/21/style/the-videogames-how-they-rate.html |access-date=11 February 2021 |work=The New York Times |date=21 November 1981}}</ref>

==Plot==
''Quest for the Rings'' is a game in which the heroes search for 10 magical keys which the Ringmaster (a role played by a human player) has hidden.<ref name="eg198306"/>

==Reception==
''Quest for the Rings'' was favorably reviewed by ''[[Video (magazine)|Video]]'' magazine in its "Arcade Alley" column where it was described as "an instant classic" with "'super hit' stamped all over it in gold letters". The combination of video game and board game elements was considered to be particularly well conceived, producing what the reviewers called "a vigorous new hybrid unlike anything ever seen in home arcading."<ref name=kunkel81>{{cite journal |last1= Kunkel |first1= Bill |author-link1= Bill Kunkel (gaming)|last2= Laney, Jr. |first2= Frank |author-link2= Arnie Katz|date= December 1981 |title= Arcade Alley: 'Quest for the Rings' and 'Asteroids': Holiday Classics |journal= [[Video (magazine)|Video]]|publisher= Reese Communications|volume= 5|issue= 9|pages= 28, 116–117|issn= 0147-8907}}</ref>{{rp|28, 116}} It was awarded "Most Innovative Game" at the 3rd annual [[Arkie Awards]] where it was described as "stand[ing] out like [[Charlene Tilton]] at a [[spinster]]'s convention". Arkie Award judges commented that "every element of ''Quest'' is absolutely first-rate from the animation of the various creatures to the clean rules", and the game was additionally awarded an Honorable Mention in the category of "Best Audio-Visual Effects".<ref name=kunkel82jan>{{cite journal |last1= Kunkel |first1= Bill |author-link1= Bill Kunkel (gaming)|last2= Laney, Jr. |first2= Frank |author-link2= Arnie Katz|date= January 1982 |title= Arcade Alley: The Third Annual Arcade Awards |journal= [[Video (magazine)|Video]]|publisher= Reese Communications|volume= 5|issue= 10|pages= 28, 76–77|issn= 0147-8907}}</ref>{{rp|28, 76}} ''[[Electronic Games]]'' reviewed ''Quest for the Rings'' as part of its 1983 Players Guide to [[Fantasy]] Games.<ref name="eg198306">{{cite journal | url=https://archive.org/stream/electronic-games-magazine-1983-06/Electronic_Games_Issue_16_Vol_02_04_1983_Jun#page/n47/mode/2up | title=The Players Guide to Fantasy Games | journal=[[Electronic Games]] | date=June 1983 | editor1-last = Katz | editor1-first = Arnie | editor1-link = Arnie Katz | access-date=6 January 2015 |volume= 1|issue= 16| pages=47 | issn=0730-6687}}</ref>

